We understand that many of our families are currently being impacted by power outages and road closures. If you are able to complete attendance for today before 2 pm and access your students‚Äô learning, please do so. If you are not able to complete attendance by 2 pm or access the learning today, today's absence will be excused. If you are able to access the learning after 2 pm but were not able to log your attendance, please email the attendance office of your school tomorrow to have today's attendance corrected. Southwood, Sunrise, and Enumclaw Middle School continue to be without power and may not be able to be reached by phone or email today.

Lunches will still be served today as scheduled

Please stay safe! Our thoughts are with all of our families and staff who are impacted by the fires and power outages.
Thank you to all of the first responders and PSE workers, working to contain the fires and return power to our community!

Families and Students will be contacted by their schools in the coming weeks with information on Chromebook and Resource pick up at the school buildings. If you are a family with an incoming 6th-grade student, a newly registered student, or a family that responded to our survey with a Chromebook need you will be contacted by your school.

If you have a student with a Chromebook that needs a repair or has a technical issue, our Technology Department is holding office hours Tuesdays and Thursdays 8-9 am and 2-3 pm.

If you are a family that responded to our internet survey with a need for an internet hotspot, you will be contacted directly by our Technology Department.

If you have a Chromebook or Internet need and you missed our survey opportunity, the surveys in both English and Spanish are linked here on our website: https://www.enumclaw.wednet.edu/teaching-learning/2020-2021-school-year

Enumclaw School District would like to thank everyone who participated and provided feedback during the superintendent search process over the last week. We are grateful for an amazing pool of candidates who all showed interest in joining our incredible district!

It is our pleasure to announce, the position of Superintendent of the Enumclaw School District has been offered to Dr. Shaun Carey. His passion and commitment to student and staff learning and growth will keep our district moving forward with our mission and theory of action. We are excited to welcome Dr. Carey to the ESD family!
text:
Enumclaw School District would like to thank everyone who participated and provided feedback during the superintendent search process over the last week. We are grateful for an amazing pool of candidates who all showed interest in joining our incredible district!

It is our pleasure to announce, the position of Superintendent of the Enumclaw School District has been offered to Dr. Shaun Carey. His passion and commitment to student and staff learning and growth will keep our district moving forward with our mission and theory of action. We are excited to welcome Dr. Carey to the ESD family!

Sending a HUGE THANK YOU to all of our School Lunch Heroes who continue to provide over 1,000 meals to our students each day!

"They are providing more than just nutrition. One little boy was SO EXCITED about what was in his lunch. "Mom, this is just like the stuff that we get at school!! This milk is in the same kind of carton that we get at school!!" It was that connection with something normal from school that gave this child an emotional encouragement. What you are doing matters so much to these families!!" - ESD Family Support Specialist

Thank you for all that you do for our students.

#nationalschoollunchheroday #schoollunchheroday #esd #Vision2020 #inthistogether

post_text:
A small group of 6th-grade ESD students decided to draw bright colorful pictures and write encouraging notes for local residents at Highpoint. 80+ copies were disinfected and then delivered to Highpoint.

These students learned how a simple, small gesture can have a big impact, how important we are to each other, and how to reach out beyond themselves.

If you look in this resident's pocket you will see one of the letters. His caregiver shared that this letter meant more than anything for him that day and it moved him to tears. He wanted to tell the student how blessed he was to receive it so he had his caregiver write the student a letter in return.

During this closure, there are still powerful lessons being learned. Great Work Students!

post_text: Last Friday, 3-5th grade students in the Highly Capable Inspiring Aspirations classes and 6th-grade students participating in Thunder Mountain Middle School‚Äôs Invent Enumclaw project gathered together at Southwood Elementary to showcase their work at the ESD Kidpreneur Business Fair and show Enumclaw what irresistible, deep, exciting, authentic learning is all about. Hundreds of people all across the community showed up to support our students‚Äô entrepreneurial spirit, find out about all of the great ideas they have been bringing to life over the last three months, and to get their hands on some of the products these students have poured their hearts into. In the end, the students raised over $3700 dollars for a class field trip and will be able to donate about 20% to Seattle Children‚Äôs Hospital. Great Work!

Enumclaw School District has a NEW Website!
Visit enumclaw.wednet.edu to check out all the new features including; improved technology, mobile response, new accessibility/translation tools, and a new interactive design. Let us know what you think!

Some of the new features include a searchable staff directory, scrolling news, social media feeds, and an interactive calendar. Click the yellow bell on the calendar and/or news posts to receive notifications when new events are added!

Please note that since Internet Explorer is phasing out, it is not included as a supported browser for viewing the new website. Please access the new site using Chrome, Safari, Edge or Firefox.

post_text: We will be starting school one-hour late today (2.7.2020). This allows for our bus drivers, student drivers and staff members to drive in the daylight. We will have our normal PLC early dismissal. We had several people driving all over our district before we lost daylight yesterday and then we were up early this morning. Many areas have receded but several areas have water over roadway. A few roads are closed. The Department of Transportation has been amazing to work with and it is evident they have been working through the night as most, if not all, roadway issues have signs (some have tipped over, however). We simply don't want our buses, student drivers and staff driving in the dark and come across an unmarked area.

post_text:
We want our families to know we are continuing to monitor our roads and have been in contact with the Department of Transportation. All of our roads are in good condition. There are no road closures at this time.

The story is different in White River. They have areas of concern in South Prairie and Wilkeson areas. They have made the decision to have an early dismissal because of those specific conditions.

Duncan is looking forward to summer!

School will be on time.

Again, Everett Cunningham (Transportation Supervisor) Ed (Director of Business and Operations) and I have been all over the district. I am grateful for these two Individuals who have had very little rest. Because of moisture last night, roads are not completely dry and can have spots that may be icy.

It is true we had one part of our district receive a lot of snow yesterday (Selleck, Cumberland, Ravensdale). I am grateful for our transportation department working with families in these areas. Can you imagine what the last 10 days have been for them? ....again, so grateful!

Our amazing custodians will work on sidewalks but parking lots can be the most difficult part of the journey so please be careful walking.

Sorry if you are tiring of Duncan photos.... he thinks he is a BIG part of this process!

post_text:
Congratulations to Garrett McGann!
Garrett's Agri-Science report received a bronze ranking at the national level in the National FFA Agri-Science Contest. He studied "The Impact of Organic and Conventional Feed Programs on Animal Growth and Development (Specifically Ducklings)"

He placed first in the Washington State Animal Science Agriscience contest. He did this by conducting a scientific study and presented his findings before a panel of judges. Placing first at the state level meant that he had to complete a written lab report to be judged at the national level. Keep up the amazing work Garrett!

The Boards of Distinction program is designed to encourage boards to examine their practices as governing bodies and how their actions and decisions impact the success of students. This award requires rigorous criteria for the performance of the school board in our school district.

This is an award and celebration to honor our entire public school system, students, staff, parents, and community!

*Not pictured Student Representatives; Sr. Emma Murphy and Jr. Olivia Quinnett.

Enumclaw School District is grateful for our partnership with the Rainier Foothills Wellness Foundation and the National Alliance on Mental Illness to bring "Ending the Silence" to families and our middle school students. This presentation, given by a young adult, who has struggled with a mental health condition, is designed to give students some basic knowledge about mental health, and how to help themselves, friends or loved ones if they are struggling.
If you, or someone you know is struggling or looking for resources text "NAMI" to 741741 or call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-273-TALK (8255). For more information on NAMI text "ETS" to 31996 or visit nami.org

#esd
#namimentalhealthawareness
#suicideprevention
#bullyingpreventionmonth
#nationalmentalhealthday

Good attendance matters for school success, starting as early as prekindergarten and extending throughout high school. Developing the habit of attendance prepares students for success on the job and in life. September marks Attendance Awareness Month, but the campaign to end chronic absence starts now! Enumclaw School District has accepted the challenge to commit to action around attendance. Learn more about chronic absence and join the Attendance Awareness Campaign today!

We challenge Orting School District #344, White River School District, Sumner-Bonney Lake School District, and Carbonado Historical School District to join the Attendance Challenge by accepting the attendance pledge.

http://bit.ly/33LuHPF

#YouBelongHere #SchoolEveryDay #WhySchoolEveryDay #psesd

post_text: It's time for Vision 2020 in Enumclaw School District! We're choosing courage over comfort as we look to the future and continue to build on our Strategic Plan. Our staff is committed to four core areas of work: Whole Child, Tiered Systems, System Capacity and Instructional Improvement. Our Theory of Action is at the center of our work and drives our teaching and learning, "If we are relentless in our pursuit of creating schools that engage students in learning that is authentic, deep, irresistible and exciting, then we will succeed in preparing all students for success in the innovation era and success in life." And we have a new hashtag as we share this year's work! #esdVISION

post_text:
Happy Last Day of School! I know this is a question I heard my parents say often when I was young, but didn't this school year go quickly? Thank you for entrusting your children to us for the last 180 school days. We have loved our time with them!
Monday night we had our graduation. Collectively, this is the ultimate goal we want for each of our students. Below is a video from Monday. I would love for you to spend four minutes to watch it today. It's always a wonderful evening!
May your days of summer be filled with magical moments with family. We can't wait to welcome your children back to our schools on September 3rd!
With gratitude,
Mike

post_text: It takes an incredibly special team to safely and lovingly deliver more than 3500 student-riders each school day to approximately 450 square miles of Enumclaw, Black Diamond, Ravensdale, and outlying areas. Our diligent drivers start the morning by thoroughly inspecting each bus and all the mechanical pieces to ensure a safe drive. The Transportation department‚Äôs attention to detail and care for our students and families is beyond comparison. In addition, it‚Äôs common to find drivers and team members taking care of others during their daily activities. They generously give their time while volunteering for community service projects, such as Neighbors Feeding Neighbors. We‚Äôre grateful to have so many kind and caring drivers to greet our students at the stop every morning and also wish them well as they step off the bus in the afternoon. #esdwonder #EnVISION

post_text:
Let's save lives together! EHS students are hosting a Save A Life Conference on Saturday, June 8th from 10 am - 5 pm. Sign up at www.kcls.org/savealife.

From our students: A group of 8 dedicated teens have created the 2019 Save a Life Conference. Our teen lead, Taylor Anglin, wanted to create "A conference consisting of multiple different classes throughout the day that will be taught by medical professionals. The medical professionals will inform the attendees on how to help and handle common medical emergencies." We want to up the odds of people receiving appropriate care or response when they are experiencing a medical emergency by getting more information into our community. This conference is for adults and teens ages 16+ in Enumclaw and surrounding communities. We've opened up registration for 100 participants, and registration is available at kcls.org/savealife. First Aid, CPR/AED, and Stop The Bleed Training and Certificates are available at NO COST! ALSO: We feed you lunch!

Students in Mr. Karkainen‚Äôs Leadership class at Enumclaw Middle School use videos as a way to inform students at their school, and in the community, about various topics such as character building, social skills, school year themes, environmental awareness, community projects, school expectations, weekly video announcements and school service projects.

Way to go Mr. Karkainen and Leadership students! #techGEMS #esdwonder

post_text: Our teachers are re-envisioning mathematics instruction from the ground up. They are using The Thinking Classroom as a model so students are completing their work in small groups while standing on their feet with very little input from the teacher, and their skills are growing at impressive rates. Students are engaged. Students are sharing strategic thinking. Students are supporting one another. Our elementary teachers are also taking an online course through Stanford University that digs into mathematics instruction and challenges traditional math mindsets. Their work in the last few months has yielded incredible results, and we are so excited to share this professional development opportunity with all of our elementary teachers. #EnVISION #esdwonder

post_text: After winning Best in Show at Invent Washington in Spokane in March, Talon Riddell traveled to Dearborn, MI to rock the NCIEE National Invention Convention at the Henry Ford Museum. He had a spectacular two days of representing Enumclaw and Invent Washington with his invention, the Horse Nom-Nom Neigh-tor. Going out of town? That's not an issue because Talon invented a feeding mechanism that attaches to the top of the horse's stall and feeds them a bale on a timed loop so families who leave for extended vacations can enjoy themselves without having to worry about their horses getting fed. Way to go, Talon! #esdwonder

Enumclaw High School Principal Aaron Lee announced this afternoon that he will wrap up the school year at EHS then his family will move back home to the Kitsap peninsula. His next position is principal at Kingston Middle School. Mr. Lee shared, ‚ÄúThe last two years at Enumclaw High School has taught me a great deal about kindness and courage as they have been demonstrated to me time and again by the EHS community.‚Äù We thank Mr. Lee for his time leading the Hornets and wish him well on his next adventure!

Phil Engebretsen has been named to lead Enumclaw High School as principal beginning July 1, 2019. Mr. Engebretsen began his education career in Alaska and California, then moved to Enumclaw High School in 2003 to teach and coach. During his teaching career he championed the use of technology and piloted many of our tech tools. In 2013 Mr. Engebretsen was selected to join the EHS administration team as Athletic Director and Assistant Principal. We‚Äôre excited to welcome him to his new role as principal!

post_text: Meet Lance, Adam and Dave, also known as Enumclaw School District's mechanics. These three individuals are responsible for keeping 66 buses in good operating condition so our drivers can safely transport our 3,597 student-riders. Each day they tend to the safety and care of operating an impressive fleet of vehicles that meet the standards required by Washington State Patrol. In addition to their duties of fueling, repairing and maintaining, these kind men also find time to help unlock vehicles or rescue keys from grates. Other days they maintain radios and install communications antennas in addition to working on the buses. We appreciate them for their kindness and skill! #esdwonder

post_text:
Congratulations to Thunder Mountain Middle School for ‚Äúclosing gaps and demonstrating improvement among student groups identified for support‚Äù! The Washington State Board of Education selected 216 schools to honor for the new equity-focused awards program and we‚Äôre proud to have TMMS selected during the first-year of the awards program.

Principal Steve Stoker attributes the recognition to their focus on quality data paired with research-based interventions. He shared, ‚ÄúThis recognition is a true testament to the hard work of our staff and students.‚Äù

The new recognition program focuses on measures to include both growth and achievement on academic indicators (proficiency, growth, graduation rate, English language progress) as well as school quality and student success measures such as regular attendance. The criteria are based on the Washington School Improvement Framework (WSIF) measures and focus on schools making significant gains in these areas.

Way to go Titan staff, students and families!

Enumclaw FFA Chapter had another incredible year at State! The F.A.R.M for KIDS team placed 1st again this year - making them back-to-back state champs! The project is completed by thirteen young agriculture educators and is then presented by the team managers. This year's team managers who earned the 1st place Championship include Lane Williams, Dustin Clarke, Gracie Boren, and Daisy Ruvalcaba!
Michaela Schulz's Proficiency Application detailing her work at a Beef Operation received first place and a gold ranking -- this means Michaela is a state champion! Her work will be sent on to the National Level for judging.
Congratulations to ALL of our incredible FFA students and teachers!!!

post_text: Pictured here are some incredibly talented student artists! In their hands are their AP Studio Art Portfolios. AP art requires a portfolio of 24 works, of which five are physically submitted and the rest are digital. Students must demonstrate their technical skill amidst a unified body of work. Their submissions include written statements to illustrate their research and application of how each piece of art represents their theme. This group helped each other often -- from critique suggestions at early stages of creating, catching edits in writing or Photoshop, to physically matting work for each other. EHS art teacher Connie Aigner says she "has been fortunate to have most of them in class since they were freshman, the year I started here . . . and especially felt proud & huge relief about what they've accomplished!" Congratulations ladies and gentlemen on completing this impressive milestone!

post_text: Collaboration and rejuvenation go hand-in-hand for our elementary teachers when they participate in Learning Labs. Learning Labs provide time for classroom teachers to gather, observe, and discuss powerful educational techniques their cohorts are using. This process also allows teachers time to reflect on current practices and then implement newly observed techniques in their own classrooms -- sometimes the very next day! Teachers learn from one another to employ best practices in their reading and writing lessons with the goal to help students acquire and strengthen literacy skills. Education means teamwork in Enumclaw School District! #esdwonder #EnVISION

post_text: This Southwood Elementary student was the manager of the Mariners! Some of our fourth through sixth Grade students participated in Junior Achievement BizTown. JA BizTown is an indoor center consisting of 21 public and private businesses, sponsored by real local businesses, where the students assume the roles of business owners, civic leaders and customers. Prior to experiencing JA BizTown, students need to complete 12 core lessons or 10-12 hours of in-class training in basic economic principals, managing a personal bank account, making smart purchasing choices and more. #techGEMS #esdwonder

post_text:
Growing lettuce is serious business at Sunrise Elementary! Students used a donated tower garden to grow five varieties of lettuce. The classroom project allowed students to taste the plants and determine their favorite, which was a surprise to teacher Diane Dal Santo with Rainbow Chard topping the list. Students chose to donate the leafy greens to the Enumclaw Food Bank.

Diane Dal Santo shared, "The Tower Garden was a great hands on activity that incorporated many academic skills that span across multiple curriculum areas including the science targets of plant cycles and adaptations. In my classroom I like to promote the traits of generosity and kindness and the intrinsic feeling in doing so. After a discussion about people in our community who are less fortunate than us, the idea of donating our Tower Garden results was born."

We love this story full of big hearts and green thumbs! #esdwonder

post_text: For the last two weeks EHS was home to many new friends in the GAPP cultural exchange program. Enumclaw High School German students are exchanging with the Karl-von-Closen Gymnasium in Eggenfelden, Bavaria. The German students spent time at school, touring Seattle, visiting British Columbia, eating at the Kettle, watching rugby games, skiing at Crystal and immersing in American daily life. What a fabulous opportunity for our students and families! EHS students will travel to Europe in late June for two weeks to immerse in German culture. #esdwonder

post_text:
It was another great week for the EHS Hornets! Here‚Äôs a recap from Band teacher Ben Barker:
This past weekend the EHS Concert Band and Wind Symphony both competed at Large Group Festival. The concert band received a II, earning them a rating of ‚ÄúExcellent,‚Äù and the Wind Symphony received a I, earning them a rating of ‚ÄúSuperior,‚Äù (the highest rating you can receive)!

Additionally, the Wind Symphony premiered a piece for Solo Alto Saxophone accompanied by Wind Ensemble, which our very own Reidan Whitcomb played the solo saxophone part to- a very challenging solo written for a collegiate level saxophone player. She made it look so easy!

The judges particularly notes the evident passion for music our students have, and the how evident the bond is that they share with one another as a ‚Äúband family.‚Äù

These kids are continually exceeding my expectations, and repeatedly seeking bigger challenges for themselves as musicians- I couldn‚Äôt be more honored to be a part of their journey!

Any Accidental Beekeepers out there? Mr. Berryhill stumbled into beekeeping after he listened to a short presentation then wanted to build a beehive. Once he built a hive, he felt the only logical thing to do was fill it with Italian honeybees. This Buzz Talk is about stumbling into a hobby and taking a path that you haven't considered. Life is full of rich (and sweet!) opportunities! We recommend watching Mr. Berryhill's entertaining Buzz Talk. #esdwonder

post_text: Southwood Elementary 5th graders are setting their sights on local government. After a recent trip to JA BizTown, the students learned about the role of members in city hall as well as the importance of voting. Teachers Brandy Stockwell and Ashley Stuenkel extended the lesson with a visit from Enumclaw's Mayor Molinaro to hear how the mayor campaigned and got to know Enumclaw voters before he was elected. One of the purposes of having the mayor present was to connect the students to local leadership. "We wanted to show that local decisions are within their reach and that these decisions actually impact their lives" Ashley Stuenkel shared. The students then asked the mayor questions about his first vote as mayor, working with other mayors, the pool, the dog park, the proposed plaza, and potential restaurants. It was another tremendous day of learning and connections at Southwood! #esdwonder
